fields.description:
It's hard to be confident if your Cmd+R buttons press took effect.
I think it's not difficult to add loader next to repo name to show users that refreshing is in progress.
But it would be great if you'll add a progress bar.
fields.summary: Show "loader" on local repository list refresh

fields.description: Normally, SourceTree will update the list of files shown in the "File status" list of the "Workspace".  However, if the name of a new or changed file is added to .git/info/exclude, the file is not removed from the SourceTree display.  The same applies if a new or changed file's name is removed from the "exclude" file, it doesn't appear in the SourceTree display.
fields.summary: Workspace file status not updated after .git/info/exclude changes

fields.description:
see https://jira.atlassian.com/browse/SRCTREEWIN-1498

When I copied a URL for cloning in Source Tree, it is stated under Repository Type that "This is not a valid source path/URL", but when I click "details", nothing is displayed in the pop-up. I am very certain that the URL I used is a valid one because it is copied from github (copy to clipboard).


# Copy a GIT repository URL to the clipboard (eg, https://github.com/dilshod/xlsx2csv.git )
# In the repository browser press the "New Repository" button
# From the popup menu, select "Clone From URL"
# In the Clone a Repository dialog, note the "This is not a valid source path / URL"
# In the Clone a Repository dialog, paste the repository URL into the Source URL field 
# In the Clone a Repository dialog, note the "This is not a valid source path / URL"
# Click on the destination path "dot dot dot" button
# Select a folder, press Open button
# In the Clone a Repository dialog, note the "This is not a valid source path / URL"

Finally,

# Move text focus back to the "Source URL" field
# Press the tab key
# In the Clone a Repository dialog, note the disappearance of the "This is not a valid source path / URL"
fields.summary: Invalid URL

fields.description:
In the log view, when I try to get the diff between two commits for a file, SourceTree shows the correct diff for simple commit but the wrong diff for merge commit

For instance, I have a merge commit with these details:
{code:java}
Commit:
 10f3bef4648a84ed74ac583a274145d3ef5d1f6c [10f3bef]
 Parents:
 d95a529449, 7aff5ad5ff
{code}
The previous version of the file is 02c6f64
{code:java}
Commit:
 02c6f6426c20567de0d588fb717781d607c30f8f [02c6f64]
{code}
When I try to see the diff in the log view, SourceTree shows me the diff between 10f3bef and one of the parents (d95a529449 in that case).

What I expect is the diff between the current commit (10f3bef) and the previous commit (02c6f64) for that file.

See attached screenshots
fields.summary: Wrong diff in log view

fields.description:
Earlier versions of SourceTree (prior to the visual refresh that I think was added in 2.x?) had the ⌘+B key binding to open the main SourceTree (previously called 'Bookmarks') window pane when the app was active, but another repository was opened.

This appears to have disappeared sometime between 1.x and 2.x, I'm not sure exactly when as I migrated from a fairly old version up to the latest (2.3.1) recently, and didn't take note of my old version sorry.

When I try and manually bind an action to ⌘+B in Settings > Custom Actions, it says I can't as it is already bound to 'Bold text', but I can't even see where that is used (doesn't appear to be in the commit message box for example).

Is there any way to bring the key combination back? For now I'm just using 'Don't restore windows on startup', but I still have to switch through ~10-12 windows by the end of the day to find the bookmarks window :)

Thanks, and keep up the great work on the app, it's brilliant!
fields.summary: Missing shortcut key to open Bookmarks/SourceTree pane

fields.description:
h3. Problem Definition

Users using an older version of Mac and SourceTree get alerts to update to the newest version of SourceTree. However, the newest version may not be supported in the old OS they have.

If the user then upgrades SourceTree, this upgraded version no longer works.

h3. Suggested Solution

Check the user's OS and do not prompt to update if their OS is not supported for the latest version of SourceTree.
Additionally, if the user tries to upgrade SourceTree manually, give a warning for the fact that their OS is not compatible with the newest ST version.
fields.summary: Do not prompt for SourceTree Updates when OS is incompatible with ST's newest version

fields.description:
h3. Problem Definition

Users have the ability to {{Rename}} their repos in SourceTree UI:  !Screen Shot 2016-10-17 at 11.00.52.png|thumbnail!
 This name that is given by the user, appears in the title of the repository window when the user opens a repo.

However, if you go to the menu {{File >> Open Recent}} the names shown there correspond to the repo folder name, and not to the repo name the user gave in ST.
h3. Suggested Solution

In {{Open Recent}} menu option, show the repository name that the user gave to each repo in ST, instead of the repo folder name.
fields.summary: As a user I want to see the Repository name in the 'Open Recent' menu in SourceTree

fields.description:
I have many tags for my repository. Sourcetree sorts those tags ascending. So I always see the oldest tags on top, and the newer ones at the end.

But almost every time when I work with tags I'm interested in the newest tags. So it would be very helpful If Sourcetree would sort the tags descending. Now I have to scroll to the end of the list to see the current tags.

Attached you'll find a screenshot that demonstrates the problem.
fields.summary: Reverse sort TAGS

fields.description:
Not sure if you all are aware, but you have given the same shortcut to two seperate actions in your menus. 

Under File, `O + cmd` is the shortcut to open a file. 

However, under Window, `O + cmd` is listed for the shortcut to open the repository browser. Looks like the UI needs to be updated to reflect the correct keyboard shortcut for opening the repository browser window.

See screenshots below for more details.
fields.summary: Shortcut to open the Repository Browser actually triggers File > Open

fields.description:
Steps to Reproduce:

1) Add custom pre-status and post-status hooks to ~/.hgrc

{code:java}
[hooks]
pre-status.better_message = echo "\nOn branch `hg branch`\n========================================\n"
post-status.better_message = echo "\n========================================\n"
{code}

2) Open a repository in Source Tree
3) Go to File Status tab
4) Notice crash message (see attachment)
5) Try to reopen Source Tree
6) When asked if you want to re-open the windows, choose "Do not Open"
7) Notice Source Tree still attempts to open windows (windows flash open) and Source Tree crashes again.
fields.summary: CRASH: File Status Tab Crashes With Custom HG pre-status and post-status Hooks

fields.description:
It'd be nice to be able to see whitespace differences in the in-line diff viewer. Right now you can ignore these changes but you can't see what has changed. Were 2 spaces removed? Did I somehow add a hidden tab?
It'd be nice too see: 
· (Middle Dot) for space
▸ (Black Left Pointing Small Triangle) for tab. (or maybe ⇥)-actually that one is better.
fields.summary: Allow option to show hidden/whitespace characters in diffs

fields.summary: Settings dialog is not clickable.

fields.description:
I feel it would benefit SourceTree greatly to bring the ui together rather than have the repo listings separate from the source control project.  Perhaps having a drawer down the left hand side of with which you could quickly toggle between projects.  For those who work on several screens and projects, it just makes it an additional hassle to locate where all the different screens may wind up.  I see no benefit (from a UI standpoint) in keeping them separate, and a single application window would be extremely helpful for keeping things organized.

This would eliminate the need for an additional screen for each repo, and someone could just toggle down the side which project they want to focus on.
fields.summary: UI - Combine Repository listing with Repo UI

fields.description:
Hi,
As my team works closely with JIRA, I thought it can be useful to develop some plugin that will integrate every push with its relevant JIRA ticket, or propose to add a new ticket if this push is not connected to any.
Moreover, the option to edit ticket status from within the sourceTree with each push.

Thanks :)
fields.summary: Integrating with JIRA

fields.description:
I have been longing for SourceTree to allow my repositories to be grouped in the Repository Browser so I can organize them by project.  Right now, I just drag them in order by project, but it is still lacking any sort of logical grouping of projects and it gets confusing, particularly when there is a new repository added and the whole thing gets a little out of order.  I am envisioning an accordion-style group so I can see the repositories I'm woking on at the time (because they are all in the same group).

Nested groups would be even better.  Then I could nest by  Project 1 > UI, Project 1 > Backend, etc
fields.summary: Ability to Group Repositories

fields.description:
I have anumber of remote repos set up in SourceTree. Yesterday I got a notice that one of them (that I have not used a very long time) had updates. I went to look, and it shows like 133000 outstanding commits. I went to look at the repo settings, and instead of my bitbucket repo, the remote origin was set to: https://github.com/CocoaPods/Specs.git

And today in a different repo, the same thing happened: the remote getting reset to https://github.com/CocoaPods/Specs.git. This was also a bitbucket repo.

Perhaps it is some kind of DNS error which results in resetting the address? That is my current theory, but odd that it can actually change the remote URL within SourceTree. I am hoping this does not happen to a repo I use regularly. Because changing the origin back does not refresh the outstanding commits window...
fields.summary: repo remote origin gets reset to github.com/cocoapods

fields.summary: SourceTree crashed when trying create remote repository

fields.description:
In this version, the shortcut to show the repository browser changed is not CMD-B anymore.
According to the 'Window' -> 'Show Browser Repository' menu item it should now be CMD-O, but this shortcut is already assigned to 'File' -> 'Open' and therefore does not  work.

This is the one shortcut I use in SourceTree so it is very annoying this shortcut doesn't work anymore.
fields.summary: Shortcut for 'Show Repository Browser' does not work anymore

fields.description:
From STSP-5110:

"Today when I use sourcetree the window for commit info (the one with author name, photo, commit hash) is missing. I think this is an issue with the latest update. I checked the forum someone asked on an old thread for the same issue yesterday. I can't find a way to get the window back. I tried reinstalling sourcetree but it's still not showing."
fields.summary: Missing commit info / window in Mac OS X Sierra

fields.description:
On Mac OS X, I am not able to connect to Google Cloud Source Repository (GCSR). I am able to connect on Windows with SourceTree. 

I get a prompt for username/password. This is not a feature of GCSR. The normal action is to set the credential.helper to look at a Google cloud SDK utility, as in:
$ git config credential.helper gcloud.sh
(This works for SourceTree on Windows, but not for Mac OS X)

Below is the error message received, after cancelling the prompt window for username/password.
(The credential.helper appears to be set to use "sourcetree")


git -c diff.mnemonicprefix=false -c core.quotepath=false -c credential.helper=sourcetree push -v --tags xhfc-remote refs/heads/master:refs/heads/master 
Pushing to https://source.developers.google.com/p/acme-it-dev/r/xhfc
git: 'credential-gcloud.sh' is not a git command. See 'git --help'.
git: 'credential-gcloud.sh' is not a git command. See 'git --help'.

fields.description:
I'm using a windows machine at work and my PC is a Mac.
I use sourcetree on both platforms and I find it quite frustrating that the name to do the same action are different between platform.

A quick example is discard on windows and reset on mac...

Can we have consistency between the two please?

It's not a deal breaker or nothing really high priority, and i guess a lot of people just deal with it, but that should be an easy fix which I think can potentially improve usability and user experience
fields.summary: Consistency between windows and mac version of sourcetree

fields.description: When there are multiple files selected in the Unstaged Files list, and you click the ••• and select "Discard file" (see "Screenshot-1") the appropriate verbage for discarding all changes to all selected files is in the resulting dialog (shown in "Screenshot-2") but in reality, only the file associated with the ••• you clicked is actually discarded; the other files in the selection are left as-is ("Screenshot-3").
fields.summary: Discarding multiple files only discards one file

fields.description:
I'm using ST on a git repo on a networked drive.
Sometimes the connection is flakey or too slow for ST, and it believes all the files have been deleted (I believe), and the reuslt is that all files are marked deleted and staged, and then all files are also in unstaged as new files. To resolve, I have to unstage all the deleted files.
This is mostly an annoyance, but is particularly problematic when in the midst of a complex rebase.

I don't exactly have steps to reproduce this, so I appreciate it's difficult to "fix", although I wonder if it would be possible to have some sort of intelegance in the file monitoring to prevent this sort of problem. If there are some logs I can view to see exactly why ST does what it does, I'm happy to provide them, but I don't know where they are, if they exist.
fields.summary: When files can't be found, they are staged as deleted

fields.description: Changes to files in git repo not being detected without explicit refresh. I have to go to View > Refresh to get "Uncommitted changes" line to show up. Standard Mac filesystem, nothing special. Stored in Documents/Projects folder.
fields.summary: Changes to files in git repo not being detected without explicit refresh
support gitlab.com as build-in remote server, which has free unlimited private repos.

fields.description:
I've got Bitbucket set up to use SSH keys for all of my git accounts. That key is password-protected. 
Ever since I've updated to macOS Sierra, Bitbucket has asked me for the password for user 'git@host.com' every time I go to push any commits. I thought this was odd, because I've set it up for SSH keys, not account passwords. I entered my password anyway and it failed. On a whim today, I tried my SSH key password, and it worked. 
I think the UI window responsible for requesting the password should be modified to specify that it needs a password for an SSH key rather than 'git@host.com' if Bitbucket wants to try an SSH key that requires a password.
I would provide a screenshot of the window in question but ever since I gave it the correct password it hasn't asked me again. I've checked my keychain for new entries today and there are none. I'll post it if it ever shows up again.
fields.summary: SourceTree asks for wrong password when using SSH keys

fields.description:
I use VNC to connect to Mac. When upgrading to latest SourceTree, it shows an annoying bug. 

In the commit view, when above section has a file selected (it's by default to show the file's diff in right panel), and I type comments if I click blank character, the file is opened. It's very annoying and I have to close the file. I must keep none file is selected to type comments. However after a while the file list is selected again automatically. 

It's not happening if I directly use MAC. It happens on VNC.
fields.summary: Commit view often open file by mistake when typing black character

fields.description:
Having Git Flow set up in the project:
1. Create a feature branch
2. Work on the feature branch
3. Switch to develop branch
4. Merge in feature branch
5. Right-click on feature branch and delete it
6. Observe 'git log' failed with code 128:'fatal: bad revision 'BranchName' ' popup

The only known workaround is to go back to bookmarks list, delete repository bookmark and add it again.

Expected: there should be no issues deleting local branches in the repo

Issue is there since 2012:
https://answers.atlassian.com/questions/94201/error-encountered-on-source-tree-git-log-failed-with-code-128
https://answers.atlassian.com/questions/289625/error-encountered-git-log-failed-with-code-128-fatal-bad-revision-paginationbranch
https://answers.atlassian.com/questions/304204/git-log-failed-with-code-128fatal-bad-revision-branchname-
fields.summary: 'git log' failed with code 128:'fatal: bad revision 'BranchName' '

fields.description:
There's a merge option, the one to create commits even when a merge is resolved via a fast-forward, that I think should be accessible without going through the full Merge menu. 

At the very least, this option...

1. Should stay set or unset depending on the last merge
2. Be visible in the "quick merge" screen
3. Be set as a global option from App Preferences.

I've included a quick video explaining the issue further.

Thank you!
fields.summary: Differing Merge Options Throughout App

fields.description:
When I'm creating a new local repository, and choose to create remote repository too, and the repository name is using special chars (in my case it was: "Etický tender"), I am not able to create the remote and I get this weird error message (see the screenshot).

I am then able to return and create new repository ("eticky-tender"), and it is successfully created, but is not linked to the local.
fields.summary: Unable to create Bitbucket Cloud remote with special characters

fields.description:
When I create new files (e.g. in PhpStorm) that are not placed into staging area then selecting "Remove" (or "Delete") option from context menu on them doesn't remove them from disk.

This worked in previous version.
fields.summary: Unable to delete new filles

fields.description:
The Windows version of Sourcetree has the 'Delete after applying' checkbox *not* auto-checked by default:

 !Screen Shot 2016-09-22 at 4.56.28 PM.png|thumbnail! 

... however, the Mac version does have it auto-checked!

 !Screen Shot 2016-09-22 at 4.56.49 PM.png|thumbnail! 

Please make the Mac version behave the same way as the Windows version! :)
It's a small thing, but it's still a thing. Thank you!
fields.summary: Stash 'Delete after applying' checkbox

fields.description:
When doing a clone of a repository from the Clone button next to an item in the Remote list or from the popup menu item labeled "Clone from URL" from the "+ New Repository" button, there is no method to choose a branch through the workflow; the default branch is always chosen (e.g., master rather than master_a in one example of mine).

Probably the best place to add this is from the Advanced section on the window where a user chooses the name and location for the clone.  Ideally, it should list the possible branches and let the user choose one, much the way that Xcode 7 and later provide, rather than requiring the user to type a branch name in.

Currently the user must do a clone by command line or another tool in order to clone a different branch than the default.

This has been a time-consuming exercise for my scenario in that each branch has different submodule branches it checks out.
fields.summary: Clone from URL does not have an option for choosing a branch

fields.summary: ssssssssss

I have a file named "Façade" (note the special "ç"). This file does not show preview diffs in Source Tree.

Screenshots:
https://cl.ly/hXdH

fields.description: SourceTree exhibits high CPU usage on Mac OS Sierra (final public release), around ~20% when idle, with no actions performed in SourceTree. git-lfs is also exhibiting CPU usage at ~70%.
fields.summary: High CPU usage on Mac OS Sierra

fields.description:
Open a repo.
Click history in the Workspace.
Click a commit.
Click a file in the commit
See the commit message with the link to Parents.
Click the link.
You should now see the parent commit.
Right click a file and choose Log.
You should now see the log of the file with the top most commit selected with the commit message showing the link to Parents.
Click the link.

I get a dialogue telling me there is no application set to open rev://5a....30.
fields.summary: Cannot follow revision links in Log window

fields.description: Get 'Login failed for your Bitbucket Server account'.  I can login in to Bitbucket directly with my password just fine.   Have tried all combinations of user name, e-mail address,  https, ssh for account setup.
fields.summary: Login failed for your Bitbucket Server account.

fields.description:
Badge on button Pull don't have update. 
On screenshot is visible what is difference.
fields.summary: No update on pull button

fields.description:
This is pretty much the same issue that has been brought up several times before, but I figured I'd bring it up yet again for the latest version.

ST over time will start to slow down (repo refreshes take longer, gets laggier), and memory usage goes very high. I'm seeing 1GB Memory usage in Activity Monitor, Private Memory is 768MB. It's using more memory than anything else, including Xcode and Safari combined.

Once I quit and relaunch and bring back the repo window, it's back down to 33MB Private.

Since I believe the app is using ARC now, there's got to be some excessive caching going on that is affecting this.

I am on 10.11.5.
fields.summary: UI slows down, large amount of memory being used

fields.description:
SourceTree has been progressively getting slower over the past few months.

It now often takes 10-15 seconds to refresh the uncommited changed view for all repositories, not just large ones.  Interface hangs while refreshing.  Selecting a changeset often takes 4-5 seconds to load changes and preview.  

I love sourcetree.  The interface is great!  However, I've found myself going back to using the command line, now that it's slowed down
fields.summary: Has progressively become ridiculously slow and laggy.

fields.description:
I realize sierra has not released yet, but it is what we need.

The sidebar options Stashes, SubModules, and SubTrees are non responsive for any clicks. They do not expand, do not show options, do not show existing subtrees or stashes. The usual "show" option does not appear.

Unfortunate for us we use subtrees for a few projects.
fields.summary: Sidebar Options Stashes, SubModules, and SubTrees are disabled (macOS)

SourceTree displays multiple dialog saying:
 > System error: It appears that the system has run out of file descriptors as described in this bug report: [http://openradar.appspot.com/radar?id=1387401.]

When it happens, those dialogs do not allow closing SourceTree itself.

fields.description:
When you launch SourceTree (a local client app), it insists on you specifying an Atlassian account. When you go to that web site and try to create one, it asks you if you're not a robot, then makes you click images like a monkey. After 3 minutes, we gave up, because it kept asking us to click more images, then pulled them away and showed others.

TWO people couldn't figure out how to get past this screen.

Why is this account thing even needed? Our Stash installation has its own account system, we really have no need to even *have* these accounts. Can you please remove this annoyance and let us get back to work?
fields.summary: Can't use SourceTree due to broken account creation

fields.description:

I thought this was worth reporting so that a plan to simplify the screen might be put on the roadmap, so that this doesn't later end up cutting options off.

fields.description:
Current behavior:

When selecting multiple commits in Log View, the Diff View shows all changes made in the selected range of commits *excluding* the changes made in the earliest commit in the selection:

 !image-2016-09-14-15-37-05-608.png|thumbnail! 
 !image-2016-09-14-15-37-20-789.png|thumbnail! 
 !image-2016-09-14-15-37-33-931.png|thumbnail! 
 !image-2016-09-14-15-37-54-086.png|thumbnail! 
 !image-2016-09-14-15-38-04-372.png|thumbnail! 
 !image-2016-09-14-15-38-23-051.png|thumbnail! 

Expected behavior:

When selecting a range of commits in Log View, the Diff View should show *all* changes made by the selected commits, including the changes in the earliest commit of the selection.

In the example shown in the screenshots above, selecting the 3 commits that make changes to each of the 3 files individually should show changes to all 3 files.
fields.summary: Diff of multiple commits excludes changes in earliest commit inside selection

fields.description:
Recently the History view has stopped displaying the pane containing the commit message, commit SHA, parent, etc. Instead there's just the list of files in the commit. See screenshot — I've added a red ring where the commit info used to be.

I've searched the menus and prefs to find a way to re-display this. Unless I'm an idiot (which I don't think I am, with 29 years Mac development experience) it seems to be just gone. The release notes don't mention anything about this either.

Could this be a macOS Sierra (10.12) compatibility glitch? I'm on the latest beta.
fields.summary: Commit info (message, SHA...) is missing in History view
Unable to update HG repo

fields.description:
Scenario
1) have modified files unstaged in workspace
2) initialize git flow

Expected: error needing stashed should either be handled automatically auto-stash process, and recover, or should not move on to "initialized" state.
Actual: thinks it's initialized, causing "next action" step to fail with "need to git flow init" error

Also expected, that quit and restart of SourceTree would look at the local repo state and detect that git flow isn't initialized-- but it remains in the bad state

work-around:
1) stash files
2) git flow init in GUI

recovery from bad state:
1) repository settings->remotes, click "edit config file"
2) delete the git flow sections at bottom, save/close file
fields.summary: Git Flow Repository Init Failure proceeds to initialized state

fields.description:
When adding version tags to specific commits I include the build number in parentheses on some of my projects. 

These could be of the format `2.0.1(235)` or `2.0.0-rc.15(227)`. When shown in the branch overview however, these are only being displayed as `2.0.1` and `2.0.0-rc.15` respectively. The rest of the UI dealing with tags shows the parentheses including their content.
fields.summary: Parens and their content in git tags are not being displayed

fields.description:
Git 2.10's new color.diff.* setting causes errors.

I set the new color.diff.old/new setting as follows.

git config --global color.diff.old "red strike"
 git config --global color.diff.new "green italic"

Then, SourceTree showed this error panel (the attached screenshot), and the graph view in history in SourceTree does not appear.
fields.summary: Git 2.10's new color.diff.* setting causes errors

6. A new repository created in remote, but no any code file are pushed into it

I tried many time. This issue always happens.
fields.summary: Menu command "Publish to Remote..." crashes.

fields.description:
I log into BitBucket with my Google ID.

Bitbucket asks me to verify my Atlassian account.

Atlassian refuses to recognize the password that JUST worked this morning (only thing that changed was me using my Google ID to log into BitBucket).  

AND Atlassian's emails for password resets are not arriving in my email inbox.  

Everytime I go to BitBucket support, I'm redirected to this page.  Frustrating and silly are two words to describe this system.

This software has literally locked me out and I'm out of a morning's worth of work because of it.
fields.summary: I'm locked out of my BitBucket account

fields.description:
Github has publicly stated that repository polling is bad practice, yet SourceTree still ships with polling enabled by default. 

Source: https://gist.github.com/michellini/a05f3068f29107caab88

Please consider changing this to Disabled by default, and even potentially warning people of the pitfalls of polling when they attempt to enable the feature.
fields.summary: Disable Repository Polling by Default

fields.description:
We are using gitflow with semantic versioning. This means that we have tagged releases like "1.2.3" etc. The tags list gets very long after a while.

It would be nice to be able to group tags in folders so that major and minor automatically went into folders, listing the actual tags. 

So we would have a folder called "1" containing folders of all minor versions. The minor version folders would contain the actual tags. That would clean up the interface a lot!
fields.summary: Group tags by version "Semantic tag groups"

fields.description: I can no longer expanding the Branches or Bookmarks sections in the sidebar.  There used to be a "hard to find" gray link called "show", but that now doesn't appear.  This makes it harder to switch branches, and I cannot work out from the interface how to close a branch.  I used to right click the branch in the sidebar.  Screenshot is attached.
fields.summary: Sidebar sections can no longer can be expanded
